      "title": "Wargaming for Improved Acquisition: What Does It Take?",
      "summary": "<p>A few months ago, I attended a panel discussion for a wargame simulating rapid industrial mobilization for armed conflict. Conducted by a leading university, with teams composed of former senior defense officials, the game probed how government and industry collaboration would play out given minimal coordination before the onset of a crisis. On the panel, the defense leaders confessed how infrequently they engaged with industry in real life to plan for a national emergency. This declared lack of public-private planning for large-scale conflict matches what I&#8217;ve experienced as a defense planner and wargame developer: Outside of rhetorical claims at annual</p>\n<p>The post <a href=\"https://warontherocks.com/cogs-of-war/wargaming-for-improved-acquisition-what-does-it-take/\">Wargaming for Improved Acquisition: What Does It Take?</a> appeared first on <a href=\"https://warontherocks.com\">War on the Rocks</a>.</p>",
